BLOCK A — MITRE ATT&CK Fundamentals

Goal

Understand what MITRE ATT&CK is and why every SOC, Blue Team and Threat Intelligence team uses it.


---

1. What is MITRE ATT&CK?

MITRE ATT&CK stands for

> Adversarial Tactics, Techniques and Common Knowledge



It is a knowledge base of attacker behavior collected from real-world cyber attacks.

It is NOT

❌ Vulnerability Database

❌ Scanner

❌ Antivirus

❌ SIEM


It is simply

> "How attackers behave after attacking a system."




---

2. Why was MITRE ATT&CK created?

Earlier defenders only knew

> "This malware attacked us."



Now defenders ask

How did attacker enter?

How did attacker move?

How did attacker hide?

What data did attacker steal?

How can we detect this next time?


MITRE ATT&CK answers these questions.


---

3. Core Structure

Think of ATT&CK like a movie.

Every hacker follows a story.

Recon
↓

Prepare

↓

Gain Access

↓

Run Malware

↓

Stay Inside

↓

Become Admin

↓

Hide

↓

Steal Credentials

↓

Move to Other Systems

↓

Collect Data

↓

Exfiltrate

↓

Destroy/Impact

MITRE documents every step.


---

4. Three Important Terms

Tactic

High-level attacker objective.

Example

> Gain Initial Access




---

Technique

How attacker achieves objective.

Example

Phishing Email


---

Procedure

Real implementation.

Example

APT29 used spear phishing attachment.


---

Remember

Goal
↓

Tactic

↓

Technique

↓

Procedure


---

5. Why Barclays cares

Suppose your KYC AI system exists.

Manager asks

"Can attacker steal customer documents?"

Instead of guessing,

Security team maps

Recon

↓

Phishing

↓

Credential Theft

↓

Privilege Escalation

↓

Access DynamoDB

↓

Exfiltrate Documents

Now you know

where to detect

where to stop

where to monitor



---

Interview Line

> "MITRE ATT&CK doesn't describe vulnerabilities. It documents attacker behaviour using tactics and techniques so defenders can build detections and improve security controls."




---

BLOCK B — Tactics 1–5 (Attack Begins)

These are the first stages of an attack.

1. Reconnaissance

Attacker collects information.

Examples

LinkedIn

Employee names

Email addresses

GitHub

Public websites



---

2. Resource Development

Attacker prepares tools.

Examples

Register domain

Buy VPS

Create phishing website

Develop malware



---

3. Initial Access

Entry point.

Examples

Phishing

Public-facing app exploit

Stolen VPN credentials

Supply chain compromise



---

4. Execution

Run malicious code.

Examples

PowerShell

Bash

Python

Office Macros



---

5. Persistence

Remain after reboot.

Examples

Scheduled Tasks

Registry Run Keys

Startup Folder

New Service



---

Memory Flow

Find Victim

↓

Prepare Attack

↓

Enter System

↓

Run Malware

↓

Stay Inside


---

BLOCK C — Tactics 6–10 (Expand Control)

Now attacker already has access.


---

Privilege Escalation

Become Administrator.

Examples

Kernel exploit

Sudo abuse

Token impersonation



---

Defense Evasion

Avoid detection.

Examples

Disable Antivirus

Delete Logs

Obfuscate Scripts



---

Credential Access

Steal passwords.

Examples

Mimikatz

Keylogging

Browser password dump



---

Discovery

Learn environment.

Examples

Who am I?

What servers exist?

What software exists?


Commands

whoami

ipconfig

net user

hostname


---

Lateral Movement

Move to other systems.

Examples

RDP

SSH

SMB

PsExec



---

Memory Flow

Become Admin

↓

Hide

↓

Steal Passwords

↓

Explore Network

↓

Move Sideways


---

BLOCK D — Final Stages (Achieve Objective)

Now attacker reaches the goal.


---

Collection

Gather data.

Examples

Documents

Database dumps

Emails

Screenshots



---

Command & Control (C2)

Talk to attacker's server.

Examples

HTTPS

DNS tunneling

Reverse Shell



---

Exfiltration

Steal data.

Examples

Cloud upload

FTP

HTTPS

Email



---

Impact

Cause damage.

Examples

Ransomware

Delete files

Encrypt database

Stop services



---

Memory Flow

Collect Data

↓

Talk to Hacker Server

↓

Steal Data

↓

Destroy / Encrypt


